{
  "answer": "**No poem in the Falsafa corpus matches this exact description.**\n\nI conducted extensive searches using distinctive phrases from your query (\"hidden from his own gaze\", \"drinks the cup of twilight\", \"bitterness of human existence\", \"riddle\" near \"human\"/\"man\"/\"gaze\", combinations like \"rivers winds stars sun human\", etc.) and broader terms (\"riddle\", \"rivers stars\", \"winds stars\", \"sun cup\", \"twilight sun\", \"bitter human\"). These returned either zero results or unrelated passages (e.g., \"riddle\" appears in Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, chapter 44, and Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 44, but without the described imagery or themes).[^1][^2]\n\nI also reviewed poetry-heavy works like *Old English Elegies* (17 chapters, including *The Wanderer*, *Deor*, *The Ruin*), Cynewulf's *Andreas*, *Elene*, *Juliana*, and Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara* parts, reading several chapters directly. None frame humanity as a \"riddle hidden from his own gaze,\" contrast it with \"self-content rivers, winds, stars,\" depict a sun \"drinks[ing] the cup of twilight,\" or close with a \"lament that nobody shares the bitterness of human existence.\"\n\nThe corpus (37 works, mostly philosophy, smṛti texts, and select literature) lacks this specific poem. It may resemble elegiac or Sufi themes (e.g., transience in Old English poetry or existential reflection in Urdu verse), but no match exists.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 44 (*Zuhd aur Rindi*), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/44-zuhd-aur-rindi/translation/#p-5cbc5a).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 44 (*Gar khamoshi se faida ikhfa-e-haal hai*), [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/44-gar-khamoshi-se-faida-ikhfa-e-haal-hai/translation/#p-710e03).",
